A Republican Strategy for Resisting Obama's Re-Election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of election fraud in the United States are more rare than deaths from a lightning strike.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing U.S. federal elections.
That's why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that complicate the registration or voting process.
The phenomenon took on a new dimension after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting the right to vote in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to show photo identification and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will and take away the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
Republican authorities were quick to extend the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to show photo identification in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens— 21 million people who have reached the voting age — do not have a photo ID issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Student voters who are believed to be voting for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their school in several states.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which vote mainly for Republicans, to use the certificates issued by these clubs to vote.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
For the first time such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of hispanics.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Hispanic voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
They have also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to add some 10 million citizens to the lists.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the new voter registration rate in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early voting period.
During the 2008 Florida general election, 33 percent of early voters were African-American, although the latter made up only 13 percent of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with immigrants from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted early.
In contrast, whites, who, forming 76% of voters, among those who voted early were only 46%.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters actively oppose the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This made it possible to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo identification.
However, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing in them an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win a presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate cancer screening: to take the test or not?
In fact, the PSA test produces sometimes erroneous results, false and sometimes false positive, which lead to useless medical intervention.
Men, who are already reluctant to undergo a medical examination, have something to doubt even more.
To take the test or not?
We asked the opinion of two experts.
Studies conducted in the United States have observed numerous cases of infection among the groups studied, so the data obtained are difficult to interpret and difficult to develop any clear recommendations.
Another study, this time European, found a different mortality rate in those patients who underwent screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, after 12 years of follow-up, that those who were not screened were 30 to 40 percent more likely to have metastases.
Therefore, I would recommend taking the test starting at age 50, or from age 40 if one of the direct relatives had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision as soon as the cancer is detected.
Cancer can be both aggressive and sluggish.
The patient needs to explain the degree of risk of his cancer, offering him possible options, without mandatory treatment of prostate cancer, which does not pose a danger to life in the long term, but making a choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
To date, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not undergo treatment, as their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to life.
We will offer them active surveillance, and if the disease begins to progress, we will begin treatment.
Increasingly, we are accurately defining the criteria for deciding who should or should not undergo treatment.
Thus, I would recommend taking the test anyway.
But it's also important to consult your doctor to determine whether or not you need to take this test.
In collaboration with the International Association of Urology, Movember has created a tool to assess the pros and cons of taking a PSA test.
This document (in English for now, a translation will be available shortly) can be downloaded from: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Prevent illness
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure to prevent cancer.
Despite the progress of scientific research, maintaining a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of disease.
It is believed that if all people ate well and moved enough, 30% of cancer cases could be prevented.
"If no one smoked anymore, that figure would rise to at least 50%," said André Beaulieu, a spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Association.
However, it is estimated that 10% of cancer cases are caused by heredity.
Several types of cancer remain completely unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Association, smoking control remains a priority, despite the decrease in the number of smokers.
Smoking is associated with 85% of lung cancers.
And it is a risk factor for many others.
It causes enormous harm to people's health.
"Even today, there are 1.5 million smokers in Quebec," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
An encouraging fact: 10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is reduced by half.
Weight
According to THE CAR, overweight and obesity also contribute to the onset of the disease.
They increase the risk of cancer of the breast, colon and rectum, esophagus, pancreas and uterus.
"Studies show that regular physical activity throughout life protects against colon cancer," the association adds.
Nutrition
The association also recommends limiting your intake of red meat.
In too large quantities, it increases the risk of colon cancer.
Sausages should also be avoided.
Preserving meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogenic substances.
"The latter can harm the cells of the body and lead to the development of cancer," the Association explains.
Vitamins
In recent years, many scientists have been investigating the effects of vitamin supplements on cancer development.
But at the moment, the results of these studies can not be called unambiguous.
According to the SCC, studies of vitamin E give conflicting results.
If one of them showed a reduced risk of developing prostate cancer, the other gave the opposite result.
The assessment of the effect on cancer development of vitamin D is also not completely clear.
However, Mr. Beaulieu emphasizes that it is important to discuss your concerns and family history with your doctor.
"Taking the test does not lead to cancer."
Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the announcement that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused quite a stir – and with good reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the Universe, no less.
It is also the last particle whose existence has been predicted under the Standard Model – our best, or at least the least imperfect, description of the nature and behavior of matter – but which had not previously been discovered empirically.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data presented this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is not yet enough for full confidence.
Let's imagine that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let's see what this means.
There is, in this world, one law that is completely inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general terms,  in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find respectable citizens, called fermions, who prudently obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, the bosons fuss, a vile gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything — at least not that principle— which means they can end up in the same place at the same time.
According to the site (by the way, quite extraordinary) Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and "force particles", through which the main forces of nature spread and to which the Higgs boson belongs in some way.
These same bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "courier" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle that has an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon – and therefore one of the bosons of "force carriers".
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be "broken".
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you need to achieve very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That is why a huge particle accelerator is needed, like the one operated at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - to achieve such huge energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never hold on to the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, whereas others (like a photon, by the way) do not.
So, what can all these studies "bring," Ms. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (CM), and this also allows physicists to find a discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of the CM.
In addition, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be revealed, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant drawbacks, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or for dark matter, which forms approximately 80% of the universe (oops!).
But so far, CERN has not found such discrepancies.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the average person's daily life are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there is none.
Look: in the very early 60s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell Labs could not even imagine what kind of revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally seen more as a "laboratory gadget."
Imagine...
And besides, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original purpose, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and has earned the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die... | "Dolg"
The Commission for a Dignified Death in Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume soon, while a bill is being prepared.
Nevertheless, much remains to be done in this crucial area.
"Duty" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monteregi.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him from the inside gave him a two-year reprieve.
"I was given five years, I lived seven," he says, between life and death, lying in bed at the Victor-Gadbua palliative care shelter in Beløy, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, it's impossible to prepare for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table on which there is a delicious lunch, he gives up and agrees to be helped to eat.
He cheers, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, lead him to the bath.
Courage before ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is to be cured of my diarrhea, it's humiliating," he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this ailment.
"Over the course of a lifetime, we are taught that a man should urinate standing up," says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois' shelter.
Regressing to the state of a child is for some an unbearable humiliation.
"It all depends on a person's ability" to come to terms with decline, he argues.
Since, according to many people involved in palliative care, important events happen in the midst of this decline.
Patients who are admitted to the Victor Gadbois Palliative Care Home are all cancer patients.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses does not provide any more care, called "curative".
Ms. A., 89, is most afraid of dying "conscious of suffocation."
But the disease allowed me to get to know my children.
"I have good kids," she adds.
"I don't want anything else in life," she says, before allowing her to put a mask to make it easier to breathe.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
At the Victor Gadbois Shelter, with the help of a group of volunteers, they provide body care and nutritional assistance.
This is the palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one place in palliative care facilities for every 11,700 residents.
This is very little, given that sooner or later we will all die.
Here life continues in the best conditions that are possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors of the shelter.
Whether it's physical, emotional or mental comfort.
To the dying, we will agree to provide mouthwashes of brandy or Pepsi, depending on what he asks.
We no longer force diabetics to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought a beer to Mr. H., who died tonight.
In the morning, his son finished this beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as well as patients," says Natalie Savard, director of nursing.
At the Victor Gadbois shelter, no day is like the previous one.
Next to a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, sitting on his pillows during a toast in his honor, a young man of 36 years dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two small children and having tried everything to survive.
"In the last six months, three to five beds are always occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christian Martel anxiously.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor Gadbois shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The challenge of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77 per cent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, the care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbois Orphanage and the Greater Montreal Society for Palliative Home Care, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this large gap in Quebec's health care system that has led many palliative care doctors to fear the passage of a law legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by the luminaries in the field of palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lyapouant, and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec's health care system is not effective enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to alleviate them.
I fear that patients want to die just because they don't get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Hopes for Helen Richard's survival were already minimal when she stopped the debilitating chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I was stopping fighting," she says.
At the same time, she herself told me that my days were numbered!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who request death thank medical staff for not complying with their request, after the palliative care team alleviates their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Society for Palliative Home Care, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we are unaware of this suffering.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want to be euthanized," it means "I want to feel better."
