Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Officials responsible for road construction, building contractors, political party fundraisers and specialists in the Italian mafia tell day after day what they know about the colossal "system" that enmeshes the construction industry, civil servants, politicians, trade unionists and the mafia.
An "industry" that has been very costly to Quebec taxpayers, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's curious how this system crumbles after all the funds have been put into action," jokes Jacques Ducheneau, a deputy and former montreal police chief.
It was thanks to him that a scandal broke out in 2011 as a by-product of the investigation of official crimes related to road construction contracts in Quebec, to which the prime minister of the time from the Liberals, Jean Charé, agreed very reluctantly.
The Duchennault Report established a direct link between industry, the clandestine financing of political parties, and corruption.
"Since the beginning of the investigation in 2010," he stresses, "the Department of Transportation alone would have saved a billion dollars in contracts" if some restrained their instincts to take a stake.
Charbonneau's commission "has already removed two mayors," he adds, hoping it will be able to "uncover the schemes behind individuals."
Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit established in 2011
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, established in 2011, joined the case and included an extensive staff of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
And, in addition, the employees of the special unit "Hammer", which after 2009 forced the "sewage cartel" of Montreal, to stop overstating the value of contracts.
A series of searches have been carried out in recent weeks and some municipal officials, notably Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, the mayor of a small town, have been charged with fraud and corruption.
Next in line is Gilles Vaillantourt, who recently stepped down as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of repeatedly receiving bribes when placing state orders.
In addition, several engineers of the Montreal Railway Service and construction contractors of Italian origin, including Tony Acquso and Lino Zambito, were formally charged.
The latter detonated a real bomb, telling the investigation about the "system" of obtaining state contracts.
For several years, Zambito gave 3% of the value of contracts concluded in Montreal to a certain intermediary associated with the mafia, who, in turn, transferred money to the party of Mayor Gerald Tremblay "United Montreal".
In the 2000s, Zambito wasted money left and right. He transferred more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about 68,000 euros) to various parties in the province, mainly the Liberals, who were then in power.
In addition, he admitted that he illegally raised funds for the former deputy prime minister from the Liberal Party, Natalie Normando.
Sewer contracts that inflated the cost
In Montreal, the "system" of corruption worked flawlessly.
Gilles Surprenan, a former civil engineering engineer, described it in detail before the commission: Over a decade, he received gifts from construction firms, invitations to travel, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey matches, and bribes totaling $736,000 in exchange for sewer contracts, the value of which he inflated.
Other officials in charge of road construction admitted to getting a kick out of inflating bills by 30-40% with fake add-ons.
Then, an organizer from the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr. Tremblay of deliberately turning a blind eye to the existence of a parallel budget that filled the party coffers with dirty money.
Following those revelations, Mr. Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a deep crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first MPs in Montreal to sound the alarm.
Mayor of The Rivière de Prairie district in the east of the island, she has resisted since 2010 the sale of a municipal plot bought for $ 5 million and resold for ... 1.6 million developers at the height of the construction boom.
70% of dirty money in election campaigns
She says that in the investigation that will eventually be launched, she will "pull on a thread that allows us to understand the functioning of the system teeming with ants to stop gangrene and identify those responsible."
She describes this process as "painful but positive."
We are in the process of cleaning up the wound, but Montreal will need its own investigative team and observer to avoid the return of questionable practices.
How we clean the house.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchennault notes for his part that "officials stole hundreds of millions of dollars," but he is particularly concerned about the role of "elected officials who knew about this scheme" but did not participate in the fraud.
Given that the share of dirty money in campaign finance in Quebec reaches 70%, he jokes: "I was told that it was just a pale reflection of reality."
The Quebec government is proposing to limit donations to parties to $100, but it said that won't change the situation: "As long as we don't strictly limit election spending, there will be dirty money in politics."
It requires a complete overhaul of the system of granting public contracts and financing parties: "We cannot sink lower; by boldly getting to the bottom of things, we can build a house on a stronger foundation, with better control and legality."
If this story casts a shadow over the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchennault urges those who laugh to look into their own backyard ...
