Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The exact opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with commission fees for their processing.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros ...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows you to exchange files between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins to make donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin, having peaked at $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about ten dollars today (rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB), in its report on the virtual currency published in October, became interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies like "credits" used to promote a video game, which are earned in the course of the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes on the network are simultaneously ledger holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers, and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, similar to an email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this ledger.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
We are talking about the hashing phase of a file, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" everything together.
The goal is to find a number that will yield a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction thus turns out to be non-rationally connected to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (in less than ten minutes) wanted to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the reward is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred millionth, which leaves another reserve...
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Bitcoin service sites have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen from reserves.
"The defect used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noise, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments in real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed a ledger and found that nearly 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant sales" were announced in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noise, another author of a manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which thus comes out cheaper.
The holder has better control over his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough just to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by phone, pierre Noise specifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal ones.
"It will be some time before Bitcoin takes hold, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB in its report suggests, by the way, to revise the various risks that are considered to be elevated today, in the event of the success of this system.
We left Afghanistan.
What's next?
French troops left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans should follow in late 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain control of its territory and for Afghans to choose their future without relying solely on us.
We suffered mainly Afghan peasants, whom we viewed as terrorists.
And ourselves, with 88 soldiers killed, and wounded and maimed.
The Taliban consist of foreign extremists, former commanders hiding in Pakistan, but also often peasants who reject the presence of a foreign army, as was the case under the USSR.
They want to protect their traditions, old and archaic, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
They are tolerated, sometimes helped by local insurgents, but they will no longer exist once the West behaves more delicately.
The departure of the French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the height of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was in order.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles, accompanied by helicopters, reached Kabul without being attacked.
From the end of 2014, there will be no Taliban invasion of Kabul.
Circumstances have changed since their insurmountable advancement from 1994 to 1996.
At that time, Kabul was empty, the country was in flames and blood because of the struggle between different factions.
Their taking control of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants, in which they were surpassed by al-Qaeda, but their situation has not improved today.
The former mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban are united in their desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main characters of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into dealers seizing state land to resell for development to immigrants who had returned from Iran and Pakistan, taking advantage of huge American subcontracting contracts.
They are discredited; most of them, by the way, didn't even fight themselves.
People, as I've heard in rural areas, want a government that doesn't consist of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have managed to american generosity: the outflow of capital is significant.
Young people are tired of war and its ideology.
They lived in the modern world during the exile in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated its advantages.
About 65 per cent of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
Public schools in the cities are filled with both boys and girls.
It is necessary to provide jobs for these young people, who will not want to return either to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of some leaders.
Everyone, including armed militants, loves mobile phones, television and Turkish soap operas, which represent the modern world, and which are watched everywhere.
At the moment, the army is there.
Will the authorities who command it be considered legitimate?
The old commanders who waged the anti-Soviet struggle are already taking measures to restore provincial militias that would not be subordinate to the central authority.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local differences, should be decentralized to a certain extent, modeled on Western countries, but the United States wanted to turn it into a centralized state with strong presidential power, eliminating the post of prime minister that had existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign control, especially ahead of the April 2014 elections.
But his country, since the 50s, and even earlier, has been dependent on foreign aid.
Industry has not been put on its feet, no dam is functioning, no irrigation system has been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except vegetables and fruits.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country devastated by thirty years of war, state control over infrastructure would be necessary.
There were rumors that Afghanistan had huge mineral wealth.
This only reinforced the sense that Western countries were there only to possess them.
With no energy to process iron ore or copper on site, no means of transportation to export through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have almost left the Mes Aynak copper deposit, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the huge Buddhist complex and remain the province's largest employers.
It is also imperative that one day, equally, Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports depend heavily, restore normal relations.
The withdrawal of French combat units was completed on November 20.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the preservation of traditional assistance: a lyceum for girls, for boys, the Faculty of French at the University, the French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, in an effort to "win hearts and minds" and accomplish the impossible task of combining aid with offensive operations, the "civil-military activity" service under the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), abolished in 2012, together with a small French public organization, has contributed to numerous public works and activities aimed at restoring agriculture in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, with the intensive involvement of local labor, were able to help contain the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, forest restoration, fruit trees, soil protection and an increase in the area of arable land.
What will we leave behind when we spend two billion euros on military spending?
A much more modest budget would help to improve the living conditions of the local population, which are very harsh in these valleys, often located at an altitude of more than 2,000 meters above sea level.
The Embassy has received dozens of written requests for small-scale agricultural activities emanating from local communities in the province of Kapisa.
To get rid of the uprisings led by foreign groups, which the farmers want, as they told me, you need to give them a little non-military support that is well controlled and goes directly to them.
The Hard Births of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a new risky move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is divided more than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it emergency powers, it has decided to play all-in.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly one week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to finish its work.
It will soon be two years since Egypt has relied on the preliminary text, which has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only deepened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusions", continuing to "violate this word" and "trample on the law".
His followers believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time that causes the Brothers to abandon the intention to explain to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy while discontent rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote positively, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I retain emergency powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted in favor of the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to get their say.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 reserve participants were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, in most cases, the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around ... time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was misconfigured.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of widespread attention, Article 2 ultimately remained identical to the article from the 1971 Constitution stating that "the principles of sharia are the principal source of law".
Salafist parties, for which the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main demands, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would allow for their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," answer liberals, who see it only as PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They point in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is alarming because "the people called upon to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy."
We can watch the birth of a theocracy."
Many liberals, moreover, are excited by the fact that the next rector of this university seems to be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no specific religious interference.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulema, but people with university education, some trained in the French system," reassures Alexis Bloche, who is preparing a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise as to whether civilian judges are competent to rule on this."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday has been criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the defense budget will take place not in the Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Nor will the trial of civilians in military courts be prohibited, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they considered disastrous for freedom.
Responsibility for blasphemy is retained, and insult is now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles are more about protecting women, said Heba Moraef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was supposed to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the Navel of the Earth and the sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and pristine nature.
"AiF" identified the five most important reasons why you need to visit Israel.
Let's Worship the Holy Places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, in which Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that God's grace descends on all who enter this "font".
And Galilee is the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding, walking on water, calming a storm and filling nets.
Here Jesus appeared before the disciples and after the resurrection.
But most of all there are shrines in Jerusalem.
Believers here pass the Way of Sorrow or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Anthony - the Praetorium - where there was a judgment, and through the streets of the Old Town leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Calvary - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Stone of Anointing and the burial place of Jesus.
Here is the symbolic Christian Navel of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was erected on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew, from which a cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is home to the holiest site for Jews, the Wailing Wall, left over from a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
By tradition, people of different confessions leave notes here with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip vertically
The ruins of the fortress of Massada are left from a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
They are located on sheer cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are fond of mountaineering can get to them on their own.
The rest are taken to this historic peak by cable car lift.
And in the north of the country at an altitude of 1600-2040 m is the famous ski resort of Hermon, where in the winter months there is a huge influx of tourists.
A shuttle bus delivers to it from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
It is worth visiting the Museum of Art in Tel Aviv.
His exposition widely presents paintings of impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Acre, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which consists of several halls of ancient Turkish baths with dummies of visitors and bathhouse attendants of that time.
In Caesarea, you should go to the unique private Rally Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no guides and souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are strictly not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells about one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section - a children's memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go into it and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
The stars twinkle.
And the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Healthier
The three main resort areas of Israel are located on the coasts of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Interestingly, the Red Sea is bathed even in the winter months, since the water temperature there does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and they swim there all year round.
By the way, this most unusual sea in the world is located on the lowest point of the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a brine that easily keeps afloat even those who do not know how to swim at all.
The scenery around is unrealistically beautiful.
They come here to undergo a course of treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and healing mud, and to treat health with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes mellitus, to put in order the shaky nerves.
Touch the mysteries of antiquity
They are kept by the old part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous Sea Route passed through it, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legends, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists love to wander through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of "your" sign, Fortune will become favorable.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for a photo shoot.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander around the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In the Roman period, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note for tourists
Going to Israel, do not worry about your imperfect English: in the country about 30% of the population knows Russian.
It is better to take money on a trip not in euros, but in dollars, which are easy to exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar - 3.8 shekels).
Urban transportation is mostly buses, but Jerusalem has a light rail, and Haifa has the country's only metro line consisting of six stations and linking the Lower City with the Upper City.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel with transfers for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Shabbat is celebrated on saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops, and public transport stop working.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels - only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat are combined.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts cooked with coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus pasta, a variety of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are a lot of fattened cats that impressively "walk by themselves."
In the evening, they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrs love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $ 37. per day (Hyundai Getz) to 188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15. per day.
A bike rental will cost 15 NIS. per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
In 2012, Israel was visited by over three million tourists from all over the world.
Most of all, citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to travel and rest.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Great and mighty" will bring to Moscow: migrants save money for the language
While deputies and human rights activists are arguing what the law on mandatory language testing will give, scammers selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
For the most part, these are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families left in their homeland.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every labor migrant will be obliged to pass an exam on knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service sector, housing and communal services, everyday life and retail.
However, over time, the FMS promises, the tests will become mandatory for all visitors.
Moreover, you will have to pass not only the language, but also Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Knowledge of the language will have to be confirmed both to obtain and to extend a work permit.
The exception is valid only for citizens of those countries where Russian is the state language.
People who managed to obtain certificates and diplomas of education before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are also not subject to the law.
Usefulness, doom and protection of rights
The network of examination points will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St Petersburg University and other Russian universities.
Migrants will be able to take tests in all cities; more than 160 such centers have already opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce testing was supported by both State Duma deputies and the Federal Migration Service.
But human rights activists, before the law came into force, many times managed to ask the press a question: what, in fact, will it give?
What will change the obligation to know the language for both Russians and visitors themselves?
First of all, - representatives of the migration service answer, - this will reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
A lot of people are now talking about protecting the rights of labor migrants, explains Viktor Sebelev, head of the representative office of the Federal Migration Service of Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights must begin before their departure.
Only a system of organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers by 90%.
Problems appear in migrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language, do not have a medical examination.
Without understanding the language, - Sebelev is sure, - the future migrant is doomed to face unscrupulous people who, under the guise of help, will shove him a "ticket" into a terrible cramped barracks, where he and dozens of others like him will languish for months without food and documents, working hard for 12-14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"At home, they are promised one thing, but upon arrival they are deceived, their passports are taken away, they do not pay the promised salary," confirms Tolib Sharipov, head of the Main Department of Labor Migration of the Ministry of Agriculture of Tajikistan.
Don't swear, nasyal!
Nevertheless, while many citizens of the Central Asian republics, going to work in Russia, admit that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they aspire, but also write in their own with difficulty.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as trouble: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get even a sensible primary education.
After all, their families have nothing to even feed their children, let alone dress them decently, shoe them and equip them for school.
Growing up to adolescence, such guys at the first opportunity go to work.
It is difficult if the knowledge of the language is bad, they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
However, with regard to the law on language, human rights activists note one important point.
Testing will be carried out only for those migrants who have legal status.
If there is no status, there will be no exam or subsequent official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers still live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Outsiders are not allowed to enter"
Many of the visitors argue that obtaining official status in our country is not so easy.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and all the same language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be done quickly and in just fifteen hundred.
Russian police officers know that we mostly have false documents, no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking for a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," Tajik citizen Umed Khushkadamov told reporters.
"Fly, don't skimp, buy paintings"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it turned out that not only migrant registration documents are fake.
Several "fake" certificates of passing language tests have already been seized by FMS employees.
Counterfeit papers are printed on a regular color printer.
Of course, they went to the new owners not for nothing: each of the migrants, hoping in this way to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as expensive as the official testing procedure: it will cost a migrant worker three thousand.
The fact that the main task for the near future is to protect the system from corruption, so that the "crusts" cannot simply be bought, both representatives of the authorities and human rights activists converge.
In the meantime, the authorities can promise guest workers who failed to successfully pass the test the first time, time to study a basic language course.
In addition, visitors who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs does not take into circulation the illegal arms market
The proportion of crimes with the use of legal weapons is extremely small
The Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia proposes to tighten the law against owners of civilian weapons.
This is the authorities' reaction to recent incidents: Firing shots at weddings when there were no casualties, and the massacre by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which killed seven people.
Police want to ban the carrying of traumatics in public places and raise the age at which you can get a gun license - from 18 years to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption Irina Yarovaya and promised that amendments to the law on weapons will be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy with the fact that the Russian authorities are trying to deal with the problem by "tightening the screws".
An open letter appeared on the network, the authors of which - representatives of various public shooting organizations - demand to abandon the "senseless tightening".
The percentage of hooliganism with registered weapons is minimal, forensic lawyer Vasily Lesnikov told the BBC Russian Service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, in the first six months of 2012, 142 crimes were committed with the use of firearms registered with the internal affairs bodies, while a total of 1168 thousand crimes were recorded during the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the tightening of legislation in the field of civilian weapons does not prevent the criminal from going to the "black" market.
Now, according to them, in Moscow you can find any weapon at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Internal Affairs claims to be in control of the situation with the proliferation of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The "black" arms market is replenished through several channels.
There are five main such channels, says retired Colonel Viktor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the structure of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a site that accepts orders for weapons
The first is the "army or military trail," that is, weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were carried by both Russian officers and Caucasians themselves," Baranets said.
The next type of "black weapon" is stolen by criminals from representatives of law enforcement agencies.
Baranets explains that this includes those taken away from police warehouses, and stolen directly from law enforcement officers.
Illegal "trunks" go on sale from military warehouses.
Explosions often occurred in many military warehouses.
"There are proven versions that some of the arson was done specifically - to cover up the shortage," says the former military.
Their contribution, according to Barants, is made by weapons manufacturers.
"Now there are private arms factories that cannot withstand competition on the international market and throw weapons from under the floor to the black market, including in Moscow," the expert says.
Another source of the black market is smuggling.
Especially a lot of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, for example, Kyrgyzstan.
"It has its own production, sometimes handicrafts, and a mafia has formed that has organized a flow," the former military man explains.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated what is the approximate share of each of the sources of supply of illegal weapons to the "black" market.
A report on this in 2011 was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Management Design.
Experts analyzed the reports of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Rosstat, criminological literature and open data of portals on weapons topics.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers write, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market ended up there "through the fault of officials whose work involves guns," the report said.
According to researchers, 17% of cases of weapons come from places of armed conflicts, in 14% of cases there are thefts at the stage of weapons production, 5% are accounted for by "black archeology".
A sales consultant at one of the gun stores, who asked not to be named, assures that the weapons found by black diggers have not been bought for a long time - too old.
Most often, as he says, for a new batch, sellers go to a military warehouse.
Through an ensign, a person buys a unit, such as a TT pistol.
They write it out to him, pass it over the fence.
"He takes it to the city and here sells it for 900 euros apiece with two shops," he says.
"True, the police are aware of all the cases, so periodically when the plan for solving crimes is on fire, they conduct a test purchase of illegal weapons from dealers," the consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
The seller and the buyer most often find each other through acquaintances.
I looked at websites, blogs, until a friend responded, who offered to come to the platform "Begovaya", where there would be a person who would take me to the "corner" where we would bargain.
I found out the price of the barrel only there
military observer Viktor Baranets
To get the barrel, I need a friend who has a way out, - says the sales consultant. - I have such a friend, but I'm not sure about it.
