"While deceiving the brain turns out to be average"
Popular among fans of modern technologies, the topic of augmented reality has recently been perceived mainly through the prism of special glasses.
First, in the summer at its annual conference, Google showed the current model, and then in November it became known that Microsoft also filed an application for the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the interactive 3D technologies group at the Cambridge Microsoft Laboratory, Sharam Izadi, it follows that for scientists of this company, glasses are a passed stage.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, creating virtual open spaces.
- Please tell us in general terms, what does your research group do?
- We are engaged in the interaction of man with machines, but at the same time we are trying to push the boundaries of this interaction.
While humanity is stuck in the mass at the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, sometimes poking at them with a finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and predict dramatic changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox is sold today without Kinect, because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else lies ahead?
- Even though Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, a lot still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is not yet very good.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projective ones.
We need to release the computer world into ours, the physical one, to make it more tangible.
To do this, however, you need to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to supplement the real world with virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
And first of all - to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
What do you think about voice control?
A popular thing, but isn't it overrated?
- It definitely can not be called a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because you do not always want to notify others about your actions and intentions.
In fact, all kinds of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not over sweeping ones, but over such stingy, short ones.
At the same time, gestures were filmed not by the camera of the device, but by a wristband, which recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
While it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future belongs to a mixed type of control, for example, gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how do you ask me to give you this can of soda?
You will say and at the same time show.
- I usually just say.
- Oh, it's going to be very hard to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what a machine can or can't do at the moment?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will mainly have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately determine human reactions.
It can be, for example, laser sensors, they give a good resolution in depth, this is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Lacking resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is something that can be based on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps.
But it's not about the megapixels themselves, but about the quality of the matrix and depth.
From the latter point of view, all the current technologies are not good enough for us - this adds work to the designers of algorithms.
That is, we must remember not only about the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also about Z.
Speed, the number of frames per second is also very important.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the current 30 k/s is frankly not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betisches of our Redmond Lab has made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms, with modern serial sensors closer to the second (60-100) indicator.
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machines.
The equivalent of such a device would be very useful to me in my work, only it does not require touches, so that there are more frames per second.
- Don't you need to increase the number of cameras?
- Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared emitter, and the second is a receiver of the reflected signal.
But the third camera is, in fact, an ordinary sensor of the visible range.
It is not used to determine the depth of an object.
Potentially more cameras could solve the problem...
Or exacerbate it by increasing the required volume of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible analogue of Kinect, play with the curvature of the location of the cameras and see how it will help in three-dimensional position determination.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that from the point of view of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, walking around all the time, holding a smartphone in your hands raised, is not very convenient, but here's what I think: the coolest option would be "transitional" augmented reality, when on the basis of a cloud platform you could switch from glasses to a smartphone, a head-up display and then everywhere.
Glasses are a very personal device, this is their strength (only you see private things), and at the same time a weakness - augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to a mere mortal.
There is one problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tactile feedback!
Hands don't feel anything!
What answers does your team have in store for this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction of man and machine.
I think the eighth may well be the addition of tactile sensations.
In the meantime, one of the interesting tricks is to use the second hand as a kind of substrate for the image.
It registers clicks perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at giving these "pictures in the air" tangibility - for example, the interference of several directional ultrasonic rays at a certain point where the finger is located gives a feeling, but so far it is very weak - as if you have blown on the pads.
There are also wrist bracelets that affect the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
To make him think that he feels what he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here lies another task that has to be fought over for a long time - how to make a person physically in a very confined space believe that he is walking on an open, almost infinite - we are working on the concepts of treadmills (not at all like in clubs), moving platforms, as well as huge balls.
While deceiving the brain turns out to be average, the work is still very much for many years.
That's what makes working on virtual reality so appealing to the researcher – many things are in their absolute infancy.
