At the meeting of the Audit Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you talked about a joint project between the Czech and German sides, within the framework of which the legislation on public procurement of both countries was compared.
What exactly was it about?
I am referring to the parallel test that we started probably two years ago.
Simply put, the point is that European legislation states how public procurement should take place, followed by national legislation and then also application in practice.
All the information was collected and, even with an unfinished check, interesting differences were revealed - simply put, our legislation can be "accurate and error-free", but in the practice of application we are inferior to Germany in some respects.
It follows that it is not enough to create more and more refined rules, it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
And actually, how can this project help you, what does it mean to you?
It is this kind of joint control that can contribute to efforts to stop the clarification of laws, the reduction and improvement of restrictions, because it does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing for a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But it is not a fact that we will achieve this by reducing the restriction of orders.
Perhaps this system will be overflowing with "papers" so that those who wish to find loopholes in this system will find them much easier than if the restriction were not reduced.
You are talking about the internal problems of practical application of the legislation on public procurement.
And how does the control system work in Germany?
Is there such an organization as our KRU (Control and Audit Office) or does it work differently?
As for the institutions, the Bundesrechnungshof, organized according to our principle, acts as our KRU, there is also a collegium that works a little differently, but basically both institutions function similarly.
In addition, the powers are to a certain extent similar, but since Germany has a federal structure, there are audit units at the level of the federal states - in this their system is somewhat different from ours.
BRH can only manage federal money, we have public funds.
Public funds in our regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of federal accounts chambers.
As for local legislation, is it easier there than here?
