Do you think the approval of this law will bring benefits or an additional burden on the bureaucracy system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope this will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise is that the rules will be "tightened" and they will not be possible to comply with.
Under the previous rules, controlled enterprises are linked to the supplier (e.g. regional operational programmes to the regional council) in that any failure to comply with the public procurement law constitutes a violation of budgetary discipline.
In this case, is it worth tightening the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system should exclude those who want to capture and abuse, but not punish those who make a formal mistake that does not affect the decision.
Such a system will only put more pressure on the bureaucracy.
And then how to get out of this situation?
Let's realize that this path will not lead anywhere.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the GDP will not bother entrepreneurs with inspections of the so-called schwartz system. What does that mean?
Is the "Schwartz system" forbidden or allowed?
The law should be established in some way, and if it prohibits something, the Prime Minister cannot oppose the work of the bodies that are charged with checking and enforcing the fulfillment of obligations.
You can say, "We're going to change this law and let it go," but you can't say we're going to pretend that nothing is happening.
The Public Procurement Law contains fairly strict rules on how and what should be formally conducted, and rightly so. This will protect public procurement.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is disqualified only because of formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly, which, in my opinion, we lack.
