Shimon Ornest: At concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
What do you think about the fact that in less than a month the end of the world should come?
This is just one of the many troubling news that we humans so easily fall for.
Together with The Tap Tap, we constantly joke about this topic and say that we are the only group in the world that will be able to collect enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
Moreover, in December you are going to give an absolutely unique three concerts against the end of the world.
Could you tell your readers more about that?
This is a nationwide fundraising event that we have been planning for two years now.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which was announced on December 21 at 11:10.
The day before this event, on December 20 at 21:00, three concerts will start in parallel in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end, roughly speaking, at the moment when the May calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean, whose time zone is 12 hours earlier than ours.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially, this was my idea, then we came up with everything together with our artist Gonza Augusta.
In addition to the fact that we want to accumulate enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to think together with the public about the state in which this world we will one day pass on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the May calendar, we have created a unique collection of items from shoes, T-shirts, bags and original keys against the end of the world. These things can be bought on the website of the www.e-tap.cz and thereby at the same time provide us with support.
The band The Tap Tap, along with other musicians, also performed an anthem against the end of the world, which is called "The end of the world is canceled."
Will the anthem already loved by YouTube listeners sound at these benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, if in the end everything works out and the end of the world does not come.
It will be sung by all the performers at all concerts at the same time.
The anthems will also be played live on Czech television at the same time.
The lyrics to this song were written and played the role of Jesus in the video Tomasz Hanak, participates in the performance of Xindl X...
How did you get involved with them?
We also cooperate with other people of Czech cultural life, as we hold many charity events and concerts.
We try to actively connect them to these projects.
It turned out that many people like to work with us, they are interested.
What will the proceeds from the concert against the end of the world go to?
For the purchase of equipment for the barrier-free educational center STUDEO, for the sixth year we have been working like this with the civic association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
Teachers regularly visit students of schools of the Jedlička Institute and hold fun and interesting events with them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the teachers, and we try to provide them with this opportunity in this way.
As part of the project of additional construction of the Jedlicka Institute, in the future there will be a separate building, to which we will move with this project.
Several musical groups and performers will perform at each concert.
What were the selection criteria?
We tried to create a program that would interest all generations, including children.
For example, In Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Barta, The Tap Tap, Marjan Bango and Jiří Suhi will perform.
All the details can be found on the www.kpks.cz website.
Do you plan any similar "grand events" in the future?
In May, we will perform for the first time at the prague Spring festival and here, of course, we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would love to hold a performance at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, if we are in the United States, would very much like to perform in Washington and Chicago.
As for abroad, you have serious plans, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you cope with the road in terms of organization and logistics??
This is not as scary as it seems at first glance.
We have five participants in electric wheelchairs, their strollers have to travel in the luggage compartment, plus a large amount of cargo and tool boxes.
Nevertheless, so far we have coped with it without problems. Czech airlines ČSA and British Airways have always been excellently prepared for us, which surprised me so many times.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went without problems.
Thanks to traveling abroad, you can compare different countries in terms of accessibility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have you come across so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other countries where everything functions better than ours, in Russia we have witnessed that in the east it is still at a basic level.
Compared to Prague, there are a lot of barriers in Moscow, and it is still a wonder that a person can move independently in an electric wheelchair in the city center.
Also, such banal things as giving way to a disabled person in an elevator are not in use there.
Fortunately, there are already public organizations that are trying to draw people's attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what, on the contrary, should we constantly catch up with the advanced countries?
There are so many things whose level of execution is far behind.
But it is important to clarify that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of those people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite normal that people with severe disabilities move independently on the streets, can go to the toilet, to the museum, and anywhere ...
It is not very common that a large number of people with disabilities take an active part in public life, in this we are a little ahead of them with The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public or barrier-free is one thing, but the moment famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers appear among us, then everything will really begin to change.
So far, these are isolated cases - people with a strong will.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but let's go back two years, what made you organize it in 1998?
I entered the Jedlicki Institute as an educator, there were many young people around me who wanted to do something.
And since I myself am a musician and I play, including the saxophone, I organized an interesting musical circle together with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our host Ladya Angelovich says, it got a little out of control (laughs).
Has popularity come only in recent years, or am I confusing something?
It's true, it helped us that we began to join the famous singers and actively work on the propaganda of the group.
We've come to the conclusion that work that no one can appreciate essentially doesn't exist.
Thanks to the funds of the European Union, we can afford qualified teachers, equipment and so on.
Did your goal be to promote The Tap Tap so well?
From the beginning, I felt their potential in their ability to do something extraordinary.
Showbiz is full of things that mimic one another.
This is logical, everything new is taken with caution, and it lasts a long time.
There are very few rare things out there, but I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us, of course, is pity, this is natural...
But this pity is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not some suffering and all abandoned personalities that we should feel sorry for.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, of course, only if they have the necessary resources.
What I'm saying is that if people with disabilities succeed, it's a shift not only for them, but for society as a whole.
Has success been ensured by the fact that you are the strict leader that many people consider you to be?
If we want to do quality work, we must be uncompromising in many things and keep a certain discipline.
But I think that's okay.
Some people come to us with a romantic performance and fly in the clouds, and when they find out that twice a week they have to go to rehearsals, attend preparatory courses and spend a lot of time on the road, they very quickly lose enthusiasm.
But this happens in any group that wants to work and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many were there at the beginning in 1998?
Only one Ladya Angelovich.
We are an open group, people come and go, this cannot be prevented.
For those who have the desire and willpower, our doors are always open.
