Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years took an active part in a number of the agency's projects.
But Poland began the path to space much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights into space, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, of the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautics" at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Peltrie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for Introduction to Astronautics.
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known world propagandist of astronautics, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to accelerate or to brake the trolley.
Information about this draisine is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Section of Armament Engineering in cooperation with professors Mieczysław Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzycki.
From the surviving materials, it can be seen that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket appeared in the specialized press, which was proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year the work "Air Rocket-Torpedo and Aviation Missile-Bomb" by the author Leliv-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on astronautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, which published four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would deal with astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
From the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (OSA) tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and in the autumn the POA became its full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the POA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became deputy chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable of covering a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were conducted on the Bledovsky wasteland.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to engage in real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aeronautical Institute was developing the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was capable of bringing a payload weighing 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Mirosław Germaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Repealing the public works law is not the solution.
Last week, the constitutional court repealed the law on community service.
The ruling sparked a lively debate in society.
Undoubtedly, it will be interesting to look at this problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in a globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the cost of labor (wages), price tension arises.
This concept should be understood as a state when the manufacturer, through the delivery of a cheap product, tries to withstand economic competition by "knocking down" the cost of a competitor in order to take a large part of the market and, thus, increase his own income.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either the transfer of production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or the disappearance. As a result, unemployment rises in those countries where the cost of labor, compared to others, is high.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility, including for the unemployment it has produced, the inevitable expenditures of the state for social needs are growing.
In general, the situation increases the reluctance of business gentlemen to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the social economic and social damage caused by them in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to cite specific statistics.
Unceremonious methods of private capital create situations at the level of the economies of individual states when the governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments are leaving their own populations to the mercy of private capital, despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes in the current legislation.
The aim is to economically force their people to submit to the dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This acts as a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool to curtail the rights of workers in the field of labor legislation.
As a result, the poverty rate increases, and with it the difference between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, for several years there has been a public distribution of food to the poor, who are not able to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is already approaching a million.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are constantly cases when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra so that they receive a living wage.
A similar scandal became known to the public in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in virtually all of the EU's southern states undoubtedly lead to the same state in which people under the pressure of a catastrophic drop in social status are forced to either emigrate, as was the case in the 19th century, or exist on poverty wages on the margins of society in the hope that someday private investment capital will come to the country.
However, the question is, where will it come from?
If capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turk, Moroccan, Egyptian, African still work for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue ad nauseam that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital stubbornly insists that the state should not interfere in the economy by controlling actions.
Next, it is necessary to answer the question whether private capital, which is now practically managing politics and the entire state, does not act for its own selfish purposes?
The unequivocal answer is yes.
Proof is the existence of virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a desperate situation, manifested in corruption, ensuring mutual benefits, in legislation where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to lack of financial resources, entrust the development of bills to private law firms that are closely connected with industry.
Then these bills are approved by the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as the Western-style constitution says, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracy is now quickly finding itself in a situation such as described by Appian in the work "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey": "The state has long been disintegrating, and the departments are engaged in violence.
Bribes, illegal receipt of favors with the help of stones and swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any prohibitions, and people went to the polls with a vote sold in advance."... decent people did not run for the post of ruler at all, in the end, one day the state was left without a consul for eight months. .. "Seriously, they began to talk about the fact that the only salvation in this terrible situation is autocracy and the need to choose an energetic person." Appian thought it would be Pompey, but it was Caesar, who finally changed democracy to autocracy.
As in antiquity, modern society is dominated by its own reckless interests without taking into account the public interest.
Private capital is no longer inherently intended to be used for public purposes.
The current result is no different from the past: an unprecedented decline of the elite without any effort to implement deeper reforms.
Hence, we must look for the reason for the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of liberal-type democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know from old and modern history.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not a solution, or at least not forever.
Under the pressure of competition both at the international and national and European levels, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
Thus, this trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the share of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in the management of the state and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
