Operation Argo: When It's Worse, Call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled after the revolution in the U.S., which had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, a positive outcome of the situation was not expected - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because this could fundamentally undermine the trust of the allies in other countries.
However, it was unable to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after talks brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election that ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck" "Operation Argo" describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult twists and turns, they finished their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, while helping an extravagant cover story, according to which they left on Canadian passports as members of a film crew looking for a place in the country to shoot a science fiction epic.
Mix of genres
The plan, which was invented by "evacuation" expert Tony Mendes, required the cooperation of Hollywood.
In order for the legend to be reliable, specialized magazines wrote about the project of the film, press conferences were arranged, a fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation have long been kept secret, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "film opus", the story of a successful venture, a scam - an example can be a number of films about Ocean's friends.
The mood in the film is constantly changing - on the one hand, the documented scenes from Tehran (the credits show iconic historical photographs of the events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lightened Hollywood passages that intersect with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other agencies - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck was remarkably able to make a career restart.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director, and his performance ceased to be the object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third full-length film, after the dark detective "Farewell, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film that is not shot in the director's hometown - Boston.
The sense of atmosphere of the place refers to qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in Argo, where Tehran "plays" Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, while reconstructing real events – the opening scenes of the embassy's fall are impressive in their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseenness that arise when a story suddenly changes somewhere.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve a lot of exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He's pretty successful with that few, sometimes figuring something out — it doesn't come out so elegantly there (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents the impending crisis at Tehran's airport, and the runway chase look pretty far-fetched).
The downside of Argo is the absent-mindedness associated with having to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it's a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the production and retro style, recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind you of one, still in a certain sense living history, as well as to testify to how exaggerated the ideas about the all-powerful and all-knowing special services are.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop."
"We were prompted to do this by the latest development, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies," the organizer of the questionnaire, Patrick Nager, told Pravo.
Among the absurdities already put forward for the nomination is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to combine the rates of insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, women have had life insurance benefits because for insurance companies they are objectively less at risk.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop people can put forward for the competition before the end of this year.
