Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which as a result harms nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain relatively small amounts of hazardous substances, or a directive on the size of the cage for chickens, as a result of which eggs have risen in price significantly this year.
Also criticized was the actual ban on the use of the term "sandwich butter" or the withdrawal from sale of classic light bulbs.
High-quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes a decision under the pressure of one or another trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (so the Czech Republic now, even under the threat of veto, defends the claims of its banks).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the European Union were supposed to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show "abnormal curvature".
At the same time, the European Commission justified itself by the fact that it only harmonizes the existing disparate national rules that complicated trade.
The EU, despite the resistance of some states, still softened the standards for fruits and vegetables, citing the fact that existing directives will lead to wasted products.
A candidate for winning the survey may also be last year's EU regulation, according to which balloons sold must be provided with a warning that children under eight years old cannot inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU turned to Us research according to which balloons when playing are a potential cause of death in children through suffocation.
Such a restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age, who are forbidden to blow into fairground pipes.
Funny ideas are born at home
