The architects of MVRDV prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikenisse and its newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"I find this building fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again," says Lisette Verheig, passing by on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, thinks: "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
All have the Internet, iPads, and e-books.
Now no one voluntarily goes to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Speikenisse, an unremarkable sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had only one opportunity to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Winnie Maas of rotterdam-based architecture firm MVRDV, a master of bold bar charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical, structures, treated the task with his usual equanimity and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the jury members looked around puzzled and shrugged their shoulders, the daring Maas folded a pyramid of size from his original gift and concluded the speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Speikeniss, the so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, this €30 million mountain has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, "Book Mountain" was awarded the second prize of the competition "The Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which previously could offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest a dairy plant, has become richer by one modern piece of architecture.
But the most important thing is that the first public building of cultural purpose in the history of this town appeared in Speikeniss.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: bookish El Dorado under a cheese cap.
There is only one elevator passing in the center of the mountain range, because real fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed on all sides, the room is bright and easily visible, the floors of baked brick and elegant street lamps unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is recreated perfectly.
The eye involuntarily searches for benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
"Usually there are bookshelves along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Winnie Maas.
We turned the classic space configuration on its head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The interior space of the book mountain is used skillfully: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical rooms.
Especially pleased are the black bookshelves, which serve as wall decoration, then parapets, then stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and civil engineers are lost in guesses what kind of unknown material it is.
"We were keen to work with secondary materials," explains Joop Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once, at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we came across a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, an artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness has been used as a lining for roots.
It's cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles last one or two seasons, after which they can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was compressed into a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplasty (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a bit like a new car and a little sneaker.
105 steps lead to the top.
Anyone who crosses the path of almost 500 meters will be rewarded in the literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and wood ficuses in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Spending on a New Soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite the many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a short time.
Wide trusses of glued wood, located perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was also here.
As well as traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who called Bukenberg "the soul of Speikenisse, which has long been lacking."
The reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from their own collection.
These books were supposed to take up empty space on the shelves of the still incomplete library - at that time it had 70,000 books.
The idea worked.
The shelves are filled to the brim.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winnie Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, now every resident is connected to this new house in some way.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it serves only for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal problem, which in professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Speikenisse wrote his literary history.
And even though they are very young and uneducated.
After all, this is only the starting point for building an identity.
Szabo: "Germans have a more important role to play"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, by doing so, Berlin is teetering on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first signaled that it would vote against the Palestinians' application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
As a result, NATO carried out this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, it is moving from the policy that, so to speak, was managed by the United States, to the German foreign policy itself.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent unified policy.
Thus, the Germans again find themselves between two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that while they are only groping for their role, they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Such a foreign policy as France or Great Britain pursues.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
This is a willingness to take a position in their national interests that does not depend on the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are largely different from those of other major states, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, in particular in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not entirely one-way communication.
But in any case, this plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the US by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States the understanding of the German position prevails.
Therefore, I do not think that it was as dramatic a breakdown as in the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests must be reckoned with.
In Europe, there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
The U.S., by contrast, has been clear in favor of the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the U.S. and many European countries?
By virtue of American domestic politics, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has, deep down, a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, the government, of course, cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that the significant differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and its position as a crucial partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be somewhat easier for the Germans if there were a single, consistent European policy, but this is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are instead forced to act on their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, if only because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, won't it really take on a major role?
Or is the leading role still hard for Germany?
Germany is not yet accustomed to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis – every time Germany assumes an important role, a wide variety of anti-German sentiments emerge.
The Germans don't just have to deal with it.
Actually, this is an old problem: you do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It must take into account a wide variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, who then remains?
