'Trademark Protection' in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous trademark, Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
But what is armani Polo?
This is a completely officially registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies from whose names it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a lawsuit.
But even then, it is unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloh, an attorney at Taylor Wessing, who specializes in trademark infringement in the Far East.
On my desk every week there is a new case of this kind.
Imitators only need to add a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci you get Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German enterprises, for example, the manufacturer of sporting goods Puma, are legally copied.
Pattloh opens a folder with the records of the trademark office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma there, an artificial name that also used the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
The fact that the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is known.
In big cities, there are multi-story department stores selling almost exclusively fakes.
However, Pattloch's case is not like that. On behalf of his clients, he opposes chinese enterprises officially receiving from the trademark office the right to use a name that is already protected somewhere else.
The Chinese call this "ban mingpai", a passenger brand.
This word is associated with "ban dakuan".
This is the name of women who hunt for rich men.
Chinese authorities do not admit guilt
"This is detrimental to business, it must be fought," Pattloh said.
"The trademark is blurred, the unique position is lost, the image suffers greatly."
Financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are in the millions, especially in the case of expensive copied products.
According to market research firm CLSA, China, with sales of 15 billion euros a year, is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is difficult and expensive to obtain the removal of dubious entries in the trademark registry.
The process can last up to nine years, with an unclear outcome.
Pattloh talks about cases in which the court rejected the claims, since after a long time the protested name became "the reality of the market."
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he will even have to pay the plagiarist, as he caused damage to his trademark in China, says Pattloh.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also famous cases about graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal dispute with construction machine manufacturer Sany, a company that had recently acquired concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
Therefore, the Chinese still have the right to use an emblem similar to the Mercedes star.
Geely, which bought Volvo, originally used a blue-and-white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, Geely had to change it.
Fashion maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore, whose famous crocodile looked the other way.
The Chinese authorities do not consider themselves guilty.
The CTMO Trademark Office in Beijing confirms that in 2010 there were difficulties due to a lack of staff and equipment in the premises.
But last year there was a "return from an emergency in the work process to normal."
Thus, the number of pending cases of objections decreased by 22 per cent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were closed, a 75 percent increase from last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending at the department.
It's expensive to fight it.
As is very common in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, nearly a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China for the tenth time in a row topped the list of new registrations around the world, the agency said.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, a total of 5.5 million pieces.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in fees were paid.
To simplify, this means that each registration costs an average of 1280 yuan or 160 euros.
It costs many times more to protest it, as the case of the German family company Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the concern has been fighting against the Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans managed to ensure that their illegal production of fake car parts was eliminated.
However, the imitator secured the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
It was an omission of its own, as surnames in Germany are not subject to protection, says Hanno Wentzler, chairman of the board of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the trademark office CTMO rejected the claim of the Munich residents.
True, Freudenberg won in both subsequent instances, but the opposite side continues to fight to this day.
You need to be on the alert
The matter is now pending before the Supreme Court.
Wenzler hopes to bring the case to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says, "The process is extremely expensive and takes us a lot of time, money and nerves."
Internal costs are hardly accountable, the company's archive had to look through even the acts of a century ago to bring evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg fruitlessly offered the opposing side a "large six-figure sum in euros" for a settlement.
"It's clear from here how costly it is for us," says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to spread even to Europe.
Namely, in the event that imitators register unprotected trademarks there.
So, one Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather goods.
The concern has long ceased production in these areas, but despite this it was able to prevent registration.
"You have to be on the alert," Goentzler says.
Both he and Attorney Pattloch recommend that German businesses be very careful with China.
It is not enough to rely on international provisions for the protection of trademarks, rather foreigners should "register everything that is worth protecting in any way in China," says Wentzler.
Otherwise, it can cost much more than registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg loses in the last act of its trademark drama, it will have to pay the other side licensing fees for its own name, Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we will be ousted from the market in the controversial segment.
