Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Frequent viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes and hepatitis.
Pubic lice and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute believes that in at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany, transmission occurs as a result of sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydial infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea, and human papillomavirus.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in our country is relatively low - but about 20 percent of new HIV infections fall on this group.
Chlamydial infections are much more common among young people than among other population groups.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people from 15 to 25 years old.
We also often have a human papilloma virus among young people.
How does the number of infections change?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory registration.
The incidence of syphilis, according to the Robert Koch Institute, more than doubled from 1697 cases in 2001 to 3698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2700 cases.
This is about one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
In infectious diseases, ulcers in the genital area, complaints during urination, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as vesicles or seals may occur.
However, often they are not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can I protect myself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not give one hundred percent protection.
After all, partially the causative agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread by contact infection and through close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent changes in sexual partners.
With early diagnosis, most STIs can be cured and long-term consequences avoided.
