"If he calls a referendum, we will go to his palace and throw it away," said opposition leader Yasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been avenged," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Khaled Ali as saying.
Many judges also said they did not want to observe the referendum, which would make it invalid.
"The Quran is our constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, in turn, called for the opposite demonstration, but, out of precaution, not in Tahrir Square, but after mass prayer on the other side of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
It was attended by a large number of women under veils and adherents of the Salafis, who shouted: "The people demand the application of God's law."
They demanded from Morsi: "Cleanse the country!" and assured: "The Koran is our constitution."
The power struggle over the symbolic square where it all began provoked a state of almost civil war.
Morsi's followers obviously did not want to take that risk.
The Muslim Brotherhood said both opponents and supporters of the draft constitution had spoken loud and clear.
Now it's time to let the people decide at the ballot box which direction the country should go.
The majority is for the islamists' project, it is considered a done deal.
"The concept of 'human rights' is never mentioned"
Hafiz Abu Sayeda is furious with this accelerated constitutional process, which, in fact, was supposed to last until February with the participation of all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EDR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this, he was beaten, sentenced, arrested.
And now the words "human rights" are never found in the new constitution, he regrets in an interview with Welt am Sonntag.
Morsi's expanding influence over all three branches of government in the state has disappointed the lawyer.
These measures represent clear blows to the democratic rules of the game and will lead Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening the civil state, the president de facto annulled it," Sayeda laments.
After all, without civil society organizations, democracy cannot function.
Sayeda feels that everyone has abandoned him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of the directions on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There could be a price to pay for that.
A demonstrator in Tahrir Square warns: "You are creating a monster that you cannot control."
Norwegian Rakfisk: The Most Foul-Smelling Fish in the World?
Norway's population of five million has one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but throughout the world.
Perhaps the secret of this country's success has something to do with the local addiction to one extremely fetid fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sportswear.
Leave them there for a week.
You'll get the smell-numbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's most famous delicacies.
I'm in a small town called Fagernes, a three-hour drive from Oslo.
Snow-covered views are all around. It is very beautiful, but an indestructible characteristic smell is spilled in the air.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for up to a year, depending on what kind of soul you need to achieve.
As dusk falls and it gets colder, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes dedicated to this, shall we say, exciting dish.
"It is eaten raw and washed down with a glass of aquavit, a local cumin vodka," explains Havard Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and part-time "rakfisk general" who runs the festival.
Everywhere around us, people eat diced fish and wash it down with considerable portions of alcohol.
"Someone likes aquavit more than rakfisk," says Havard.
This drink is able to kill the smell.
I try a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - not much different from a portion of sushi that you have been carrying with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from completely different times, the times of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish in the autumn were soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water.
Then, in the deep winter, when the fish had already fermented well and thoroughly, it was extracted and, muting the perception of alcohol, was eaten.
It is still in the memory of the last generation that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted here by jobs, high salaries and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a long-standing rival, and not so long ago and much more prosperous neighbor) come here en masse to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat fetid element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here – a small glass of beer or a sandwich will set you back £9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world news, and most of the country's residents seem to be satisfied with this.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, the racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the terrorist attack is called "what happened on July 22."
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
At the heart of Norway's current prosperity is the growth (since the early seventies) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
"However, oil is not the only reason we thrive," says Anna, our waitress carrying trays of aged rakfisk, a woman with long blonde hair and strikingly blue eyes, the epitome of Nordic well-being.
We are such a people - as you call it - reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks perfect English.
We don't like to be on display, we're not bragging.
Norway handles its oil very carefully – most of the oil and gas industry's revenues are invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was littered with money they didn't have, Norway was thrifty counting all costs.
"As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, that's enough for happiness," says Anna.
"And there's a rakfisk," she adds with a light-hearted laugh.
I'm standing in the snow in line for some food - I've had enough.
Here's a hamburger with moose meat - it's certainly exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for an even greater number of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
My hotel hosts a special dinner dedicated to rakfisk, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a live television broadcast, which shows the presenter in a bow tie, surrounded by plates with a rakfisk.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jürgen, what grade did you give for the best fish out there in your mountains?"
"Yes, Havard, here's our assessment."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls out of a chair, perhaps after sorting through the aquavit.
Or maybe just inhaling the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto will have a difficult start to his career.
As Mexico's newly elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the difficulties he will face and the mixed expectations of his country's population.
Traffic in Mexico City is now in a particularly deplorable state.
The city is congested with traffic at the best of times, and since Monday steel barriers have been erected, cutting off several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was done not to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will put on a presidential sling and take the reins of power of the country.
He faces a daunting task.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderón, who is now stepping down, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has already claimed about 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government declares to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence," Mr. Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the White House Oval Office.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Peña Nieto's political career was developing alongside the U.S. president as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country's capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straightforward Man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is remembered fondly.
Residents credit him with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort sector and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached via one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are strikingly different from the pothole and pit roads that were previously on this site.
Plaques with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We pin our hopes on him for real and serious change," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman for the Peña Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that our country so desperately needs, particularly in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the accusations of vacuousness made by the opposition to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very dedicated to realizing his vision for the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman, and above all, a man who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different view of the former governor.
The municipality of Nezahualcóyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under highway overpasses, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also of a severe nature of this metropolis.
Earlier this year, troops were brought in to pacify drug gangs in those areas; and violence against women is particularly acute here.
Several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found in a vacant lot near a vast landfill in the past two years alone.
More than a thousand women have been killed in the state of Mexico during Mr. Peña Nieto's governorship, far exceeding that in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juárez, whose name has become a household name when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to Mr. Peña Nieto's opponents, it can be said of him at best that during his tenure as Governor he has failed to cope with the problem of femicide.
In the worst case, his administration is accused of completely ignoring this problem.
A resident of a concrete house like most houses in this dilapidated neighborhood, Irenaeya Buendia can barely hold back tears as she shows me pictures of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her partner.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before," Ms Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten and her body had already stiffened.
Mariana's mother retells the story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to a crucifix on which only one word is inscribed: justice.
That, they said, was denied to this family.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip cop, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just take everything they say on faith and keep quiet.
But this is wrong, it is impossible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around," she says.
Wearing the presidential sling on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will shoulder the heavy responsibility with it.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime, and the new president has promised to make addressing the problem a priority during his rule.
"I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was governor," says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear the most.
Bradley Manning has not complained of mistreatment, the prosecution said.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning's stay at a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is seeking to close the case on the grounds that Manning's conditions of detention were harsh.
A U.S. Army private is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution sought to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of the many opportunities to file a complaint about the ill-treatment he said he endured while in a military prison.
During cross-examination at a pretrial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein said records of weekly visits to Manning by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
Cross-examination of the defence motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his imprisonment were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was conducted the day after Manning claimed that he intended to commit suicide while in custody.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, Prosecutor Fein, along with Manning, reviewed reports that were completed after visits to Manning by administration officials during his stay at Quantico Prison, where he was held under a high-security prison regime from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked Friday about the reports, Manning admitted he rated the treatment by prison authorities as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports reviewed do not contain any complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about the conditions of his detention, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed verbal concern about these issues and that administration officials who visited him had discussed the issues with him and stated that they would be addressed, but had not recorded them in writing.
"They wrote down 'there are no problems' (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation," Manning says.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission that considered suicidal intentions that he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to get the "injury prevention" removed and the conditions of detention relaxed.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that the limited regime of imprisonment - a level lower than the regime of supervision to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I was fine so that they would lift the injury prevention regime ... to improve the standard of my life, from my point of view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months, before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had suicidal thoughts in Kuwait and that he had once lost consciousness due to extreme heat.
He explained that psychologically it is very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is being decided, and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell — at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day — all alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was forbidden by the rules.
According to Manning, while sleeping, he was constantly hit in the eyes by light penetrating from outside the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he rolled over in bed at night, he said he was awakened and forced to roll over on his back.
Manning's attorney filed a formal objection to Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
Also on Friday, a judge questioned Manning about a statement he made while testifying Thursday that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates at a morning check."
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Responding to questions from a judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from a security guard's order that he had to throw a blanket he could cover for, but admitted that no one had directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer he could have used a rubber band of panties or flip-flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, Manning testified, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to endure during his imprisonment and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to ask Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and challenge other charges as excessive.
A resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, with the prosecution expected to insist that conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico under the rules governing the detention of those arrested with the strictest possible regime.
Among the charges brought against Manning are aiding the enemy, illegally facilitating the publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defense, and stealing state property or documents.
If convicted on all counts of the indictment, he could face life in prison.
My crisis of national identity is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the country's residents of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent are torn between the two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked through the arrivals corridor, approached the border control zone and froze in place.
The signs indicated two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called a Mexican all my life.
It's just a conventional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York call themselves Italians.
Later, I settled on the complex "Mexican American" design.
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conventional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
So I pulled out my American passport and got in line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago, when Mexico's newly elected President, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto was eager to talk about the boom of the Mexican economy, thanks to which Mexicans would now, with the same success, be able to stay in Mexico, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a kind of North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-age issue.
Most Americans never thought about the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, at gunpoint, forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, as soon as any US statesman mentions at least a word of criticism in the direction of Mexico, complaints are immediately heard in the press and among the elite of Mexican society that Americans encroach on the sovereignty of neighbors.
And montezuma's descendants are filled with militancy.
Mexico's relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the U.S. is the most complicated.
Want to talk about grievances?
There are enough of them.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities for themselves in this country, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for one reason only: at some point in their family history, someone – father or grandfather – did not have the opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - dark-skinned, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and got good jobs, but we will not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national identity is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider our own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most members of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We respond to them in kind.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class citizens, as fake Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough and our ties with Mexico aren't strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind a silk curtain right now, finding a well-fed life in the U.S. but losing our spiritual connections.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the U.S. as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans — Mexicans have a clearer understanding of their national identity, and Mexican Americans are offended.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many Mexican Americans I know don't feel like they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
By getting the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
And in the U.S., they call us Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations are already not complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to serve as sorts of Ambassadors for Mexico and represent its interests in the U.S.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could persuade political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, absolutely.
It won't work.
Too many grievances in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country to be so beautiful.
Sorry, but deal with it yourself, Amigos.
And rightly so.
If some Mexicans still can't forgive the United States for what it did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans are still offended by the way their relatives were treated in Mexico as recently as possible.
Yes.
Perhaps we have more in common than I thought.
Old Battles in the New Middle East
Ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is long-term peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There are familiar, pointless arguments about who started first; many buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed; For the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip landed in the vicinity of Israel's capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly bogged down in their eternal conflict, change has come to the Middle East.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the "Arab Spring" swirled many established realities in the rebellious storm, and the Palestinians and the Israelis failed to stay away from the whirlwind that shook the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggles will become even bloodier than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give reason for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, is implemented, this week's clashes have only strengthened the position of security forces on both sides.
Leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group's leaders have been killed and 1.7 million people trapped in one of the most populous and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is increasing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements grows in the Arab world, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
Resurgent regional leader Turkey, which was once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out in support of Hamas; its example was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing states in the Persian Gulf.
Triumphant Hamas supporters claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the militant group Hezbollah, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow the rule of Bashar al-Assad, and further to Jordan, where the king's authority is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant shift in the balance of power in the region occurred on Israel's southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement has strengthened under President Mohammed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic alignments, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
Militarily, Hamas has been defeated.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep soundly, at least for a while.
On diplomacy, the U.S. has remained true to its unchanged position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Although approximately 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by a wall that enters the West Bank – a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state – and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party – in preparation for the January 22 elections – has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What's the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they put all the power in the West Bank in their hands, won't they launch rockets from there toward Israel, as their brethren in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and firmly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Hardliners may win; however, their calculations can be refuted by the Arab Spring.
Despite the fact that the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not have the warmest feelings towards Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense portion of Israel's budget is larger than that of all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on the cease-fire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change emerges in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a ticking time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus blown up in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic dimension – the growth of the Arab population – only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas come at a cost with growing discontent among the international community.
Both sides need external momentum.
What remains is the only solution that sensible representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper, tirelessly call for: the formation of two states and Israel's ceding of territory in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which is long overdue to cut off arms shipments to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are in a better position than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967 in view of the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also work to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in recognition of Palestine's virtual statehood.
President Obama also has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
Since returning to the White House, he has remained reluctant to engage in the issue.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on uniform packaging for cigarettes came into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of disease-affected parts of the body stand out in contrast on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world practice, the Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of dull olive color with terrible pictures of body parts affected by the disease and images of children whose health was undermined by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced mandatorily from this Saturday, is the names of stamps that are printed in the same small print.
These are the harshest conditions in the world for the design of packages of tobacco products.
Australia's federal government says the purpose of the measure is to deter young people from smoking by depriving this bad habit of fashion status.
The basis of this decision was the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100, never become smokers.
"It is obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey with the help of packaging design," explains Health Minister Tanja Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest proportion of smokers in the world, so these changes will not particularly affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering the possibility of taking similar measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market on which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will lead to serious consequences, different from those conceived by its initiators," said Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply many more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, argues that demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a case in an Australian high court where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and expects a new batch.
It's good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the very part of the population to which these measures are directed.
Following the passage of a number of laws in Australia that made cigarette television advertising and support illegal and their support for sporting events, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites from doing so.
"If you're selling tobacco products and you're left with just this small loophole, the idea of promoting your product online will seem extremely tempting," explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of reviews of trademarks written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is this really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims under the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that the trade relations of all these countries with Australia are very insignificant.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government has discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory placement of photos warning about the dangers of smoking.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia defiantly disobey innovation.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
"You just grab a cigarette and hide the pack in your pocket," explains Victor El Hague, who buys cigarettes with a photo of a tumor of the oral cavity on a pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little girl.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco shop in central Sydney, argues that the same packaging has made it more difficult to arrange goods on the shelves.
"It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, but now it's four hours," he complains.
"The government should have banned cigarettes altogether, we would have said, 'What to do, okay, it's over, close the store,'" he says, throwing his hands up.
Being bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not such a bad thing.
On this Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical problem and was replaced by another plane that we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help here.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and specialists in child development speak in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations, it's not so bad for us and our children to be bored.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which perhaps contributes to creativity.
And since in today's world we are all constantly in front of some kind of screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should strive for boredom?
Yes.
And at the same time, no.
We'll come back to that.
I used to believe, like many, that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, argues Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at Canada's University of Calgary and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
"Boredom actually boasts a very ancient history," he says.
On the walls in Pompeii, Latin inscriptions about boredom dating back to the first century have been found.
That being said, it remains an open question about how we understand boredom.
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that understanding and seeing boredom has often changed.
After studying the research materials on this topic and asking a question to a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people "want, but cannot do something that would bring them satisfaction."
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn't do something they'd like to do.
With apathy, you don't want to do anything.
Central to the boredom experienced, he says, is "the disruption of attention and the associated deterioration in mood and the feeling that time drags on slowly."
By description, boredom may seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances around them, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when in fact it's just hard for us to focus on something.
In their study, "The Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Prof. Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading a journal.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of an irrelevant television program turned on in the next room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume so that they could barely be made out, and a third group listened only to a voice recording without an extraneous audio track.
Those participants who heard a low-volume TV noted that they were bored, more often than others - they had difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we're trying to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can cause boredom, says Mark J. Smith. Fenske is an associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "like peering into the flow of products on an assembly line looking for marriage, distracting music can help avoid boredom."
It is believed, he continues, that when people start swaying in a chair or drawing doodles on a piece of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions simply help not to relax physically.
"The study showed that children who are not forbidden to fidget and twirl learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit still," says Professor Fenske.
At some points, we all experience boredom: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting film.
However, different people show varying degrees of propensity for boredom.
In the 1980s, to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special "boredom bias scale."
To determine the score on such a scale, questions and statements are used, for example, "Much of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I am too much interesting, so there is not enough time for anything."
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys were bored more often than girls, says Stephen Vodanovic, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, teenagers in general are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personality and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he used a pager to contact nearly 400 teens and their parents 7 to 8 times a day.
He got the following results: 32% of teenagers said that they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said that they were bored outside of school.
At the same time, only 3% of parents noted that they are bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data on boredom would be now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that "adolescence is the peak of the tendency to boredom," mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Back to my original question: Is boredom helpful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme manifestations, it can, as research shows, push people to absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling or abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
"So our brain tells us that we should do something else; that's boredom," says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this same brain does not always know what exactly is better to do.
If you get bored and direct that energy to guitar playing or culinary experiments, you'll make yourself a better person.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and that will soon pass.
So if your child gets bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop getting bored, but he will not learn to fight boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and employment, says Professor Fenske.
"And such self-regulatory skills are used in a variety of situations," he argues.
Your child learns not only to engage himself in something on his own, he also learns self-control in general.
I don't think boredom should be celebrated in any way.
However, it should not be considered something bad either.
Rather, one should learn to feel comfortable even outside of the continuous flow of action and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"What we see is that we need to experience boredom more often, even though boredom is an extremely unpleasant, unquenchable desire to do something meaningful," he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
"In today's world, we're used to constant overstimulation of the senses," he says, "and when there's silence, we get lost and don't know what to do."
It is not yet clear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana in colorado will be applied.
Anthony Orozco, a nineteen-year-old soccer player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, is charged with a felony that will soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: possession of a small portion of marijuana and the pipe in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orozco said that one september he and his friends were in Lamara and were driving in a car on the prairie near the border with Kansas when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco received a subpoena for drug possession and possession of a drug use device — minor offenses, each of which is owed a $100 fine — and a court date has been set.
"We are treated like criminals," Mr. Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has been going on for weeks since colorado voted to legalize the use of marijuana in small quantities for entertainment, the resolution of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law as on the place of consideration.
Marijuana-related felony charges have already been dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington state, which has taken a similar measure.
Police stations have already stopped bringing charges against people aged 21 and older for possession of small doses, which will be considered legal once the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
However, in more conservative Colorado counties, prosecutors have decided to try existing marijuana-related cases and are still being prosecuted for possession of the drug.
At the same time, some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous regions of the West are voting to prevent the emergence of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their places.
"It's all developing so rapidly that I don't even know what to expect next," says Daniel J. Smith. Oates, police chief in Aurora Township east of Denver.
Regulators in Washington state are also scratching their heads puzzled.
They will have to form rules to determine the procedure for licensing the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done before December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in regulating marijuana use, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
"Colorado has a more streamlined market, so they'll serve as a good example," said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Regulatory and Marketing Board.
But now no one can do more, Mr. Smith admits, than put forward some proposals and hope that it will work.
"We don't have a real precedent that we can target," he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will go into effect on Dec. 6 and will plunge the state into a state of uncertainty for a whole year, when there is no state licensing system yet, and the right to own marijuana is already legalized.
And there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be solved during this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order for "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on its sale at a distance of 1,000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
"It will be particularly difficult to locate licensed marijuana businesses within cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs," explains Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly created marijuana legalization research group.
On Nov. 21, Chief Constable Oates of Aurora sent an email to his subordinates stating that the city attorney's office would no longer prosecute 21-year-olds for possession of small amounts of marijuana, and that police were ceasing to convict people of these violations "from now on."
Chief Of Police Oates said police would monitor the city's compliance with the rules governing the activities of persons growing marijuana for medical purposes and would prosecute illegal drug dealers and distributors.
The attorney for Weld County in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, presents a stricter approach to the matter.
After the vote on the bill, he said prosecutors would continue to prosecute marijuana possession, mainly to encourage those who use it to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 individuals are charged with possession of two or fewer ounces of marijuana, although many of them are accused of other violations.
"It is the responsibility of our institution to prosecute acts that are considered criminal at the time they are committed," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The reaction has been mixed even in places like Mesa Rural County, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Police at Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, are no longer prosecuting adults for possession of a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to drop charges in already open cases related to marijuana possession.
"I believe that it is our direct responsibility to enforce the law until it changes," he says.
Despite the fact that 55% of Colorado residents who took part in the vote supported this decision, the inclusion of marijuana for entertainment in the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the contradictory reaction of residents in different parts of the state has exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state's experiment with marijuana.
"District attorneys have a cultural barrier to this," said Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney representing marijuana convictions and a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
"They've been chasing people for this for so long that they can't really accept that it's no longer a crime," he says.
Colorado and Washington — the first states in which small amounts of marijuana are treated in the same way as alcohol — are destined to become an experimental field on a national scale to test the very idea of legalizing drugs.
Supporters of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are waiting with caution from the federal authorities, who still plan to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a federal crime.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope the Justice Department will concede on the issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of medical marijuana traffickers and patients, the federal government has in most cases given the go-ahead for the sale of marijuana for medical purposes in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Drug Enforcement Bureau agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug adviser in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for federal action.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores, which would not have been able to open earlier than a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the marijuana trade, which is likely to be approved next week.
"We don't want to be in a position where we're going to give someone a license and then it's going to cause serious problems at the federal level," says Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still many outstanding issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I was expelled from Oxford for being a conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I've always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, the modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - free thinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying history at Worcester College, Oxford University in the late eighties, I packed my bags and left, which resulted in the first real scandal in my life.
My father couldn't stand it and started crying.
Friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn't like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from chipped cups.
It wasn't really that funny.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was systematically bullied and intimidated.
Not because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to a private school.
I was bullied for only one reason, and in this glorious cradle of enlightenment it looked like real barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a famous adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of conservatives.
You may ask, why remember this now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who hold center-right views are subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalised and ever-growing hatred of Conservative students at Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as that granted to disabled people, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at corpus Christi College's student club in Cambridge say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel unwanted" because of their political views.
They want to bring an additional representative to the college's equal rights committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only exacerbated by the recent BBC 2 documentary about student politics, Wonderland: The Young, the Smart and the Right, which portrayed conservatives as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, a former president of the Oxford University Conservatives Association, who rides in a Rolls-Royce, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver knob.
At other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made "scapegoats because of higher tuition fees."
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Conservative Association at the University of Nottingham, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing bias towards the left in the university environment.
People who don't even know us think of us in advance as brazen and violent children of wealthy parents with impunity."
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christie College, where the petition for increased protections was filed, calls the atmosphere "uncomfortable", and Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Conservatives Association at the University of Oxford, says that the attitude of student club members towards carriers of center-right views has deteriorated significantly.
"This is a threat both to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of club members," she says.
For the first few weeks at Oxford, I wasn't just in the minority, I was alone.
I went there in September 1986, a timid and shy eighteen-year-old girl.
Oxford was feverish with hatred of the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had stripped former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree by a vote due to budget cuts to higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the early days of freshman week, when students get to know each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time what lay ahead of me.
I didn't know yet that teachers not only turned a blind eye to the harassment of conservative students, but they were also happy to take part in it.
Political issues – a miners' strike, privatisation and the government's refusal to sanction the apartheid government in South Africa – permeated the wood-panelled walls of the classrooms.
In my first seminar, I needed to translate an eighteenth-century French text into English, and I wasn't prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the teacher, the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was hard for me, I stammered.
Harry Pitt was a very gallant man with a face that looked like a cake.
"Thatcherists fundamentally don't learn French or do they just lack brains?" he asked.
Other students giggled.
I had tears in my eyes.
"I advise you to take a few initial French lessons in your spare time, unless, of course, you are very busy spinning in society," Pitt said.
I went back to my room completely miserable.
That night in college, I was sitting alone at lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year English student who introduced himself as a member of the University's Conservative Association.
"I know who you are," he said friendly.
- Unfortunately, this is as follows:
Anyone suspected of sympathizing with conservatives will be bullied.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be more difficult for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour."
Later, at a local pub, I cowardly tried to be hypocritical.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The ruse failed.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contagious."
Other students picked up on his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex? One of them asked.
"They're stabbing each other, right?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the decriminalization in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet like-minded people only under the cover of night?
Will I be forced to become Labour and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years began to seem like hell to me, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only professor in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for being conservative, but also for being Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He hardly appeared in college.
He despised him for his provincialism, pettiness, and adherence to the Marxist-Deterministic view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents' house in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased metropolitan friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were accepted there.
"But it's the best university in the world," he said plaintively.
- They can't do that there, just not in a city of slumbering spires...
Even my communist friends have always behaved flawlessly."
His moist eyes became cloudy.
"Don't make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You're going to break my heart if you drop out of university."
I was exhausted from the constant travel to London and my emotional defense was waning.
My friend, also a conservative, could not stand the pressure and abandoned his beliefs.
The following week, during a seminar, when another history teacher called me an "enemy of the people" quite seriously, I decided to do the same.
Burning with shame, I confessed that "my parents brainwashed me" and called them "old fools."
The respite was short-lived.
The final nail in the coffin of my oxford career was destined to be hammered by my father.
At that time, he wrote two columns every week for publications owned by Rupert Murdoch.
My door was locked.
I didn't come out, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a crybaby and a rag.
But at eighteen, no one should be the object of such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
It is all the more sad because it was Oxford, which not only produced fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and free thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
About the exhibition "Valentino: The Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitz and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of Valentino: The Master of Sewing, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his "home" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is garavani's "il signoret", but it could not have been written without his eminent clients.
Valentino always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, is replete with personal letters and photographs signed by the most noble aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social uplift, from a humble tailor from the town of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international "elite."
Being in love with the royal court is nothing wrong with that.
"They at least don't extinguish the cigarette butts of their cigarettes on your gorgeous carpet, as some fine pop stars do," says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitz.
In the '60s and '70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an incomparable host and receives guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all really enjoyed visiting his chalet in Gstaad," explains Heini's ex-wife Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
And despite this, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza recalls the charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to dinner at his house, it was after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty invitees were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style manifested itself in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its decoration, in food, in music.
"Valentino made each of the guests feel important and loved," recalls the "top model", whose work with the fashion designer began in 1995 during the Haute Couture Fashion Week in Paris.
"He never goes out of fashion because his sketches are real works of art," she concludes.
Pedigree Parade
Garavani's life is not a story of obsession, but of falling in love with full reciprocity.
He loves people with good upbringing and high titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries of Somerset House has been transformed into a glamorous podium sixty meters in length, which offers a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of models and has to parade on the podium, contemplating the "spectators" of dreams that sparkle with masterpieces from Valentino, such as the dress that Jacqueline Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costume that Monica Vitti used in "Night", or a coat of wool and leather,  which belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
In this audience, such names as Sibylla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sofia Habsburg shine from the models.
Nati Abascal and fashion designer, in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino is like a first love, "impossible to forget."
I remember it perfectly.
These were pants, a shirt, a "vest" and a jacket from the fall-winter collection of 1971-1972.
"It was a gift he gave me," says Nati Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him to others for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty," adds the former Duchess de Feria.
I really like the colors he uses: they have a lot of light and they "fit" his face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and trendsetter Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg also can't forget the first time she dressed in Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed that I would have the age and reason to put on one of his evening toilets...
Finally that hour came in the late '90s.
I bought my first Valentino dress to wear to a feast in the castle of my cousin, Prince Edward de Ligne.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with ruffles, a pleated corsage and a strapless neckline.
"It was a dream that came true," says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his passion is timeless," explains this Italian aristocrat, who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg keeps her festive dresses from the fashion designer with "the utmost care... because a dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories that accompany it."
The "king" of fashion
The great finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos from Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the fashion designer calls his seamstresses) to make this outfit of ivory silk with pearl inlay, twelve types of different laces and a train of four and a half meters.
According to journalist Susie Menkes, the greatest authority of the specialized press, the dress represents the milestone of high fashion of the late XX century, "the return of clients from the high society."
Drugged for many years by the "lifestyle" of the elite, now Valentino himself is its best representative.
Knight Grand Cross (insignia of the highest rank in Italy), Chevalier of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters, awarded the Order of the Legion of Honor, Garavani collected as many honors as any of the spouses of his clients.
"My attention has always been drawn to his sophistication, his calmness, his neat and impeccable appearance," recalls d'Arenberg.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Musée d'Orsay.
He was sitting at a table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribe, a great friend of mine.
"He was immaculate, time doesn't exist for him."
If that's what the princess says...
The hardest profession in the world: miners from Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make their living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulfur dioxide rising from the depths of the Earth freezes on contact with air.
Breaking off huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, puts baskets on his shoulders and carries them up along a steep rocky road.
The summit of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters high, is only 250 meters away, but it takes more than 40 minutes for exhausted movers to climb at a snail's pace, barely keeping their balance and carefully groping for the road so as not to stumble and fall off a cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to one tourist from France who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys from a circus and, tiredly carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandy Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, to say it better, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical industries, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Since the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk," explains Anto, who usually performs three daily carriers.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels overwhelmed, however, they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
While this seems minuscule for such an inhuman effort, it is three times more than what he would earn in the field.
"Daily wages for miners are very high by local standards, where coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (€1.2) a day and an average monthly wage of two million rupees (€167)," explains a longshoreman who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.2) a day and the plot was not as heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason that in Indonesia is as crushing as sera: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are some Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs, and his eyes are watery due to toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes hard, he coughs constantly, and his eyes water because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dreams.
"I'll work for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning, because sulfur does not cease to flow out at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines among the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small lantern connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters pull baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of a volcano.
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work at their own expense and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don't even get a fraction of the 30,000 rupees (€2.5) fee for photography, which, along with the entrance ticket for 15,000 rupees (€1.2), the guards of this reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule people.
"This job is for livestock, not for people," said Badrusin, a stocky porter of 42 years who has spent three decades on Kawah Ijen since he left college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilograms, he says he will tolerate the job "as much as he can" because he needs money to educate his three children between the ages of 18 and 10.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in the dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains about their serious diseases ... more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pain and shoulder ulcers that deformed under the weight of baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainick can now only lift 50 pounds in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among the thickets.
"I'm not retiring, I'm going to die here, because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide, which is missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult occupations in the world: what human mules from Kawah Ijen do.
Singapore is looking for children to save the economy
