"People are very overexertioned, housing is expensive, as well as education, and because of this, many people postpone it," says the young manager.
Other people may have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and time," says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and housing and education prices as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how hard the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, when it comes to childbearing, Singaporeans have the final say.
Personal offline - in person online
Confidentiality.
According to the dictionary of the Royal Academy of the Spanish Language, it is a property of the private or "sphere of private life that has the right to protect against any interference."
What is personal for a minor under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when discussing situations on the Internet that he probably would not share outside the Internet?
elPeriódico interviewed five children between the ages of ten and 15, frequent netizens.
In four cases, they associated the term with "something very personal," and "password and username" when they applied it to social media.
"My biggest secrets I wouldn't upload to a post," says ten-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the significance of personal on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he says.
On FB, I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games.
I also have fun with my friends.
"I wouldn't share a photo that isn't mine or someone who behaves stupidly," he says.
The boy realizes that it is bad to publish indecent photos of naked people, crimes or write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows 35 friends he has at FB and nine of his followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother knows, she has a password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just download them," he adds.
"Social media is entertainment, I can talk to distant relatives or to my friends quickly," he points out.
Without hesitation, he replies that he would never accept a request from an unfamiliar person.
I wouldn't reckon with anyone who would recommend it to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in the latter admits that he does not know 20 people added to his friends list.
"It doesn't scare me because we have something in common, music, for example," he points out.
According to the boy, no one rubbed into his trust and did not ask for his home address or phone number.
"If they put pressure on me or demand them, I'll just remove them from my account," he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experience of what is known today as cybermobbing.
An acquaintance of my friend was blackmailed on a social network.
He was threatened and extorted money.
"He never found out who it was," he said.
The victim, according to Jose, did not delete the account.
"Only enabled privacy".
It then explains the sequence of steps to configure the account in a secure manner.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do it if I don't like the person or if I want to.
"Although I know it's cybermobbing," he confirms.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and education and training specialist, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, you need to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a means to find information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed," she notes.
Porras points out that Academic Mark Prensky, a master of pedagogy at Yale University and author of Digital Natives and Immigrants, invented these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital Natives are them, children and youth who were born in the age of technology.
"We're digital immigrants who have to teach them while we're still learning," she says.
He explains that this topic is complicated, "because we ask them to have a certain criterion for what can or cannot be distributed, published or said, at an age when maturity is not enough for this."
"Also for them to be selective, when the most important thing for them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to show what privacy is to children and adolescents is to ask questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it is useless," she adds.
Porras then lists some options: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing it online?
Or, would you like it if they published a photo of you like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you sign photos from parties, are you asking for permission from other people to tag them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing in every moment?
Another point is to let them know that they should behave online just like they do offline.
The rules are the same.
"Outside of the Internet, a person behaves with respect, responsibility and other principles, so it should be in social networks," she says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, a university lecturer, primary education professor and education consultant, explains the need for heads of households to read social media policies in good faith.
By understanding each of the points, they have good reason to talk to children about the background to opening an account online.
"For example, age and what is allowed to be distributed or published," he says.
According to Gaurdia, the key issue is to remind children of the lesson "don't talk to strangers."
UNASUR summit ends without promulgating the Lima Declaration
The VI Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the SIXTH Ordinary Assembly of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and The Presidential Administration indicated on the main page that it would be handed over after the closure, but then confirmed that at some point it would be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief press statements.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound with the message "closed meeting, sound is prohibited."
A small amount of information circulating among reporters was passed on by spokespersons for some UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not in Peru.
The only document distributed during the day was a list of participating presidents, angering hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian presidential administration sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this is Umala's statement, not the official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and that time, despite the fact that the press insisted on it, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was also not distributed.
On the official website of ASPA, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that transmission systems were provided for all journalists, but limited the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the ruling of the International Court of Justice, which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear statements from both sides, as part of an indictment that Lima has brought against Santiago.
"We will abide by and enforce a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently submitting to this international court," said Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of differences, pacts and international tribunals," Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake against the backdrop of the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice came just after Colombia challenged this week the Pact of Bogotá, under which it recognized submission to the verdicts of that international court following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of Brazil's presidents, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and the directions of action for 31 projects were approved among South American countries, the amount of proposed investments amounted to $ 17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residence agreements."
He said actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizens' insecurity and against organized transnational crime, actions to increase access to medicines, affordable Internet access in all corners of South America and taking into account the risks of natural disasters in an aggregate and effective manner."
As Europe is in crisis, "the economic unification (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our productive base and foresee a better future for our cities," Humala added.
"We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South American spaces, especially in village and border areas ... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes," the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five belong to Peru, and are limited to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at greater communication with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-join the Union of South American Nations," from which she is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united, and to have good relations between its neighbours was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In that sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending a regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to hold talks in a respectful manner about the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of an international court challenged by Bogota.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday) I may meet with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We will revise all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful manner possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also within the framework of the summit, the ministers of defense of the bloc met in advance to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which is aimed at strengthening dialogue and unanimity on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the participation of the latter is suspended.
Peru has an interim presidency in the regional bloc.
