Mortality from AIDS today - the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was told he had tested positive for AIDS.
"It was as if I was stunned," he recalls that difficult moment, despite all the tact of the doctor.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn as much as possible about it. And his efforts were justified - he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" patients in the HIV department of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he entered in 1994 after overcoming many obstacles.
He has been living with a diagnosis of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 90s, it would have been hard to believe – there were too few treatment options then, too little was known about the disease, too biased towards the sick.
So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Protection did not want to say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a sentence.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so without impairing the quality of life.
However, without knowing about their illness, many people still come when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, "a great achievement at the moment is that the survival of a patient who begins treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said the head of the HIV department of HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, citing the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious disease specialist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but the duration and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system that patients have at the beginning of the diagnosis, with the best life expectancy for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with a number of 200 CD4,  and until the age of 50, when 500 CD4 is reported.
Simply put, the above means that someone who receives an HIV-positive diagnosis at the age of 25, according to these terms, "maintaining control, will be able to live without problems until the age of 75," he explained.
To appreciate this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today averages 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the advent of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have already been recorded by May of this year; however, it is claimed that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's the way things are in our hospital.
At least for the last 12 years, we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late, because they do not know about their infected condition, that is, in the later stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: "Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out diagnostics at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection on a mass scale, for all people who ask for it."
In their proposal, experts and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (COESIDA) agree, as well as patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who turned to a private laboratory for testing, prompted only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was already at the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor.  which is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know anything.
"Since I'm going to die anyway, I'd rather three times a week," they say. But not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, do exercises, take medications.
To date, his parents only know that he has had cancer.
I live a normal life like any other.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person," said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage with his statement those who are now, in the context of World AIDS Day, afraid.
Let them check if there was a risk of infection, let them find out as soon as possible whether they are HIV-positive, so better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This message of his summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS in this 2012 year.
Condoms behind the counter
There are great gaps between health programmes and the common citizen, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara-based journalist who tackled hiv-related issues.
And the biggest is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "there is actually an increase in the distribution of condoms, we used to be given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, and this is very good, but it turns out that there are those who now still do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with snideness and condemnation, from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and health workers that teenagers don't want to hear, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; that condoms are not only behind the counters and that a hundred of them are in vending machines in public toilets in places that are often visited by young people.
This is not an encouragement of promiscuity.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, Governor Emilio Gonzalez replied when asked if it was possible to distribute condoms under his leadership.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who already practice sexual activity," he said.
Key data in Jalisco
