Given the ratification by the United States Court of Appeals of a decision that annulls the Vitro Group's debt restructuring achieved through bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico, the scenario sets a fateful precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country that has solvency problems.
It seems that procedures to support the survival of firms that are permitted by Mexican laws are not valid in the country of stripes and stars, contrary to international agreements.
In practical terms, the approval of Judge Harlene Hale's June 15 ruling in the Northern District Bankruptcy Court of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless in the face of the possibility of seizing their property on the other side of the Rio Grande.
However, the ruling opens the door to a leading glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies as evidence.
As an introduction, while the judge of the case notes that creditors should be governed by the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, located in New Orleans, says the main proceeding concerns bankruptcy proceedings pending in Mexico.
The first paragraph implies the annulment of international judicial cooperation in cases of insolvency of enterprises of a transnational profile.
In fact, for this purpose, the UN Model Law on the Unification of the Law of International Trade was created, defining the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Second, the verdict establishes that without an inter-firm vote, the critically recognized bankruptcy debts owed to the parent company by Vitro affiliates would not have achieved the majority necessary to approve the restructuring.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro was not the first time this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Competitive Industries.
It is also true that by subtracting the votes of the branches, one way or another the Vitro creditors who fought against it in the courts of the United States, namely vulture funds like Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent to 37 percent.
The Court of Appeal omits these data.
On the other hand, he blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008, affected by a serious economic crisis that has overtaken the United States, striking at the country.
So far, the gonzález Sada family firm will appeal the decision to the Court of Appeal itself so that the vote reaches its plenum, that is, five judges, since only three voted.
In the event of failure, a motion for certification will be filed that will require a review of the process by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court.
Worst of all, the court rejected a document sent by the Mexican government as amicus curiae ("friend of the court"), which describes the process that Vitro follows under the Bankruptcy Law, signaling that it exempts itself from compliance with agreements signed by both countries to link it to Article 15 of the US Bankruptcy Law.
In addition, it is noted that the country has obeyed the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, that is, the rules established for cases of interstate insolvency, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
