Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Avid basketball traveler Hector "Hetin" Reyes was associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to it, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many basketball histories as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
And before a cerebral hemorrhage confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a minor player, a Major League Basketball player, commissioner and BSN executive with Bayamon Cowboys, and president of the Basketball Federation.
"I've played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, like when I was president of BSN, CEO of the National Team, and president of the federation in the '90s," Reyes recalls during Primera Hora's visit to his home in Bayamon, where he has lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating by making this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia collected over his long journey, bear witness to this.
Bayamon in the Heart
With the greatest emotions, he keeps those that remember his journey through the Cowboys, from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when it was the 15th anniversary of his performance as a co-agent or contract agent.
"Those were my best years, which I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboy Championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or executive.
There were many years of joy, including five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year Jerome Mincey made his BSN debut.
From that moment on, Ortiz, who was a great administrator, became the head of Cuco, who was a great administrator," Reyes said.
I remember gene Bartov, who was on his way here and was at the University of Alabama(Birmingham), saying to me, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7 feet tall."
"Do you want to?"
And that was the beginning of Mincey, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartov then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who was granted citizenship and became one of our top scorers.
I remember saying that if Mincey had brought the championship to Bayamon, Gauss would have helped win another one.
I enjoyed the cowboy championship with Gauss, but already at a distance, because by 1988 I was already listed as the head of the federation.
By then, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and Minsi's achievements in the national team.
I remember winning for the first time against the United States during the Olympic qualification tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Championships, where we got fourth place and it should have been bronze, if not for that Canadian referee who forced us to replay the final game, Reyes said.
Is that team from the 1990 World Cup the best team you've ever seen?
It is among the best, as is the one that won against the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the one from the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and defeated team USA, which was pretty similar to the one that won us bronze at the World Championships.
That team not only included Mincey, Gauss, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and Piculin (Ortiz), but also young (Javier) 'Tognito' Colon and James Carter, brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Quixote' Morales, who was unable to compete in '90 due to a knee injury.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic Qualification Tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With role players like Nieves' Canito, Pablo Alicea and a young Rolando Hurruitner replacing players suspended for a mess in the Mar del Plata Pan American Championship, we won gold against all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Piculin Ortiz.
His performance in international tournaments is impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated this level the way Piculin did.
And that's without regard to his career in the various leagues he's played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
This is a very difficult question.
We had very good youngsters including Julio Toro, Flora Melendez, Carlos Morales, Raimond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the young, I really like the work of Leo Arilla.
What do you consider your main achievement in the federation?
Participation in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s the BSN had up to 17 teams per season.
What do you have left to do?
There were things I wanted to implement, like regionalizing smaller categories.
For example, that boys from Ponce play only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys are traveling and playing too much, and that's unnecessary.
At the very least, I see the fruits of mandatory certification and a course for managers, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all, I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally go to basketball games.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman has died
Born on September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, Larry Hagman became world-famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.," in the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a businessman without principles, evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil predator mogul J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday night due to complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., dallas' production studio.
"Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he liked the most," his family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for a Thanksgiving fair.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was by Hagman's side when he died in a Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray confirmed in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in the liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman gained notoriety on television for his decent-type role in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie," broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie girl played by Barbara Eden and begins to live with her under the same roof.
He was also the main character in two comedies that rarely appeared on the air, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that propelled Hagman to the pinnacle of fame.
A CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in his entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan "Who Shot J.R.?", designed to create hype around an episode full of emotion in which Hagman's character is nearly killed, generated international discussions and millions of dollars risked at bookmakers.
It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at that time.
When the november 1980 episode was answered, an average of 41 million television viewers watched it and turned Dallas into the second-most-watched entertainment program in history, after the 1983 MASH finale, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. prevented her and then threatened her that he would accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt official with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be placed for treatment.
"I know what should be on J.R.'s gravestone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be said, "Here rests the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
That's the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, both on and off screen."
He is unforgettable and indispensable for millions of admirers around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who are lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new dallas issue aired a few months ago with great success on TNT.
The recording of five episodes of the second season has already been completed and the sixth was in production, the channel reported.
Warner or TNT have not yet made a statement on what will happen to the series after Hagman's departure.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who shone in such classics as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan."
Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to him in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
