A course that explores "The End of the World" begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic phenomena such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charme decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had a compelling lure: the end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan calendar, December 21, which many people seized on as proof that the end of the world was coming.
But Charmey had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the financial crisis that some call the "long-termageddon," and the growing conflict where Israel would be dragged in, a place where end-of-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester of all," Sharme told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you analyze what's happening in the world now, as if we only have 30 days left, it was a really good period.
And remember that the bad is good for those who have an apocalyptic way of thinking.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the latest in history.
At Temple University, Associate Professor Barry Wacker teaches a course on "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
"We analyze why these ideas spread over time," he said, and the way in which hypothetical scenarios are proposed to trigger certain human actions.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month, students analyzed films on apocalyptic themes and studied how they relate to real-life examples.
"I tried to tell students about what is possible, probably plausible and impossible," Wacker said.
At Pennsylvania State University's main campus, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an associate professor of art history and anthropology, teamed up to teach a course called simply "The End of the World."
"We don't add '2012' to always be able to read the course again in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "imminent destruction," students must learn, prepare projects, and take final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work "until the very night that is supposed to be the end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"The seats ended in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-GPA students, which enrolled 35 students.
We received emails for many weeks before the start of the semester from people who asked if there were any more places.
Students, in turn, assure that this course is one of the most interesting.
"I love watching what people are doing to comfort themselves," said Brigid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And the apocalyptic way of thinking, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or lack thereof.
Will Vequesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had watched all the apocalyptic films.
"I've never heard of a course that teaches this," he said.
I like him.
But none of the students surveyed — let alone the professor — said they believed the end of the world date of Dec. 21.
"Our first draft touched on a Mayan prophecy, and in some ways we discredited it," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old final-year student at Temple University in West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key moment on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that dates back several centuries, where people respond to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The internet has caused an increase in this speculation.
"Elsewhere, people don't think about it," he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at the University of La Salle who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered a question about whether he knew of any course about the "end of the world" there.
"The Philippines is not taking part in the end of the world," he wrote, alluding to the order of a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
